<TITLE> BTRC sues Amar Desh for defamation </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 28 (bdnews24.com)Bangladesh Telecommunications Regulatory Commission sued Bangla daily Amar Desh for defamation on Wednesday, citing a story titled 'BTRC in the grip of India' published in early October. A Dhaka court issued summons the same day on publisher Mohammad Hashmat Ali, acting editor Mahmudur Rahman, chief reporter Syed Abdal Ahmed and reporter Oliullah Noman Magistrate A.M. Zulfikar Hayat issued the summons ordering the four to appear at the Dhaka chief metropolitan magistrate's court by November 30. Tarek Hasan Siddiqui, deputy director of BTRC's legal and licensing office, filed the case, accusing the paper of damaging the reputation of the regulator and the image of the present government in national and international arenas. Amar Desh carried a story in two parts, on October 2 and 3, headlined 'BTRC in the grip of India: Concern at the appointment of the Indian citizen at the BTRC, State security to come under threat'. On Oct 8, the paper publsihed a cartoon on the same subject. The news was unfounded, said Siddiqui. Though legal notices were served, before the case was filed, regarding the report and the cartoon, the accused did not give any logical or satisfactory reply to the notices, he said. b
